I was going to skip today. Even though I loved day 6 I couldn't do everything and I was feeling very frustrated, disappointed, ashamed. I struggle with an eating disorder so it's easy for me to slip into the "just do the exercise even if it hurts" mindset. Then I realized that was silly. So I told myself to repeat day 6, I'll do it better today because I just will. But then honestly I saw that day 7 was a little shorter (crunched for time because of work) so I said, let's just try today out, try to be kind, see what happens.  And I'm so glad I did. This practice was exactly what I needed. I was feeling so shaky and lost.  Your thoroughness, talking through each point, being kind, was exactly what I needed. This not only grounded me but reminded me I can be the world for myself. I have everything I need. I didn't force myself to hike my leg up to my thigh in tree pose, didn't force myself to do anything that hurt. In the end, during the one minute of meditation, I hugged myself and teared up. Thank you, Adrienne, for reminding me of myself.

I've been doing Yoga With Adriene for about five years now, but this practice made one of her fundamental insights finally click with me. I'm usually really good at the balancing postures and always enjoy powering through those videos and feeling kind of smug about how good my body is at it. But today I came on the mat with 3 hours of sleep, 1 day before a stressful moving day, 10 days before leaving my country for another one, with loads on my mind - and I struggled. Even just lifting up onto my toes make me fall in all the direction. But I was humbled and able to laugh about it and kept trying and finally understood this message of "practicing balance and not achieving balance". I first thought I was unlucky that the balancing practice came on this day for me and I wouldn't be able to enjoy how good I'm usually at it. But then I understood that it was the exact right day. I needed it today exactly *because* I was off balance. The practice gave me the balance that I had lost in my stress. By the end of the video, the meditation seat that usually always pains and troubles me felt comfortable and I could have sat there for days. I don't know what do say. I thought today would be a horrible and tough day, but now I feel ready and relaxed and strong. Bless you, Adriene, for giving those tools to all of us. Without you, I'd have never tapped into yoga, and now I can't live without it anymore.
